FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - KAZAKHSTAN: (ZHAMBYL) SUSPECTED, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*******************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 2 Mar 2012
Source: Agricultural Sector, Kazakhstan [in Russian, machine trans., edited]
http://agrosektor.kz/news-news/1115--217-.html


The agricultural directorate office in the Zhambyl region reported that 217 head of cattle infected with FMD have been killed in the area of Moyinkum. According to the head of the office, M Asilbekov, mass vaccination has been applied in the 50 km [30 mi] buffer zone around the outbreak's location in Moyinkum, which includes 16 rural counties, reports [the national news agency Kazinform]. 4 checkpoints control the entrances to the territory of the rural districts around the FMD outbreak, applying disinfection and other preventive control and quarantine measures, including restrictions on the import and export of controlled goods. The buffer zone includes 27 628 head of cattle (including calves), and 244 650 goats and sheep. Commenting on the financial compensation to the owners of the destroyed livestock, M Asilbekov noted that under current law the amount is in the range of 72 000-89 000 tenge [USD 486.47-601.33] per head of cattle. "But it is expected that a decision will be taken to compensate the losses at market price, in the order of 170-180 thousand tenge [USD 1148.61-1216.18] and not later than within 2 months.

[byline: Ilyas Abdiev]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Zhambyl (Jambyl) province is located in South Kazakhstan, bordering Kyrgyzstan and adjacent to its capitol Bishkek; see map at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Jambyl_in_Kazakhstan.svg. For the location of Moyinkum (Moinkum), see maps at http://healthmap.org/r/1XhQ and http://www.fallingrain.com/world/KZ/17/Moinkum.html. This southern province, probably infected by FMD virus introduced from Kyrgyzstan and/or Uzbekistan, has become Kazakhstan's 3rd region infected by FMD since May 2011. For OIE reports and maps of the previous 2 outbreaks (caused by FMDV serotype O), in the west (since May 2011) and the east (since Aug 2011), which are continuing, please go to
http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=10637 and
http://web.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=10940.

An official notification with details, in particular the FMDV serotype involved, is anticipated. - Mod.AS]
